The Rev. Dr. Milne, the Manse‚ Fyvie, tells me there is a local tradition that Boece was Rector oi Fyvie. Os this l can find no confirmation, but l think the names, Fyvie and Tyrie, have been confused, as they would look very like each other in ancient script. ls it be said that Fyvie was more likely, as being a richer living than Tyrie, to have been given to Boece, 1 would remark that Tyrie in Boece’s time included what is now the parish ol Pitsligo. This is not the place to attempt an estimate of the value os Boece as a historian. lt may suffice to say that while he is pictoresque he is unscientific; that his History of the Bithops shows the same deiects as his larger work, the Hrlrtovy of Scotland,· that he seldom gives dates and never quotes autho- rities; and that except lor contemporaneous events he cannot be regarded asa trustworthy authority. He speaks os authorities for his History, Veremundus (tempore Malcolm lll.), and a certain Campbell, both os whom are otherwise unknown. Le· land’s tetrastich on Boece is as follows 2-—
